record_data.record_plain_text: PURCHASE AND SALE AGREEMENT This AGREEMENT is made and dated as of July 1, 1986, by Niagara Mohawk Power Corporation (NIAGARA MOHAWK) and Jersey Central Power & Light Company (JCP&L), Metropolitan Edison Company, and Pennsylvania Electric Company (collectively, FE UTILITIES), and Mid-Atlantic Interstate Transmission, LLC (MAIT) (together with FE UTILITIES, FE COMPANIES). WHEREAS, it is anticipated that from time-to-time NIAGARA MOHAWK or FE UTILITIES (each a "Party" and collectively "The Parties") may have excess energy available, and it is further anticipated that from time-to-time the other Party may be able economically to purchase such energy, and WHEREAS, from time-to-time either NIAGARA MOHAWK or FE UTILITIES will be selling energy (which shall define such Party as the "Seller") to be delivered to the other Party (which shall define such other Party as the "Buyer"), and WHEREAS, both NIAGARA MOHAWK and MAIT are interconnected with others not a party hereto and both Parties anticipate that from time-to-time they will have transmission capacity available to provide transmission services (which shall define such Party as a "Transmitter") to each other for delivery of energy to or from such other parties, and WHEREAS, NIAGARA MOHAWK and FE COMPANIES wish to provide herewith the terms and conditions pursuant to which purchases and sales of energy and provision of transmission services will be of mutual economic advantage. NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual obligations and undertakings set forth herein, the Parties to this AGREEMENT covenant and agree as follows: ARTICLE 1 - TERM 1.1 The period during which any purchase and/or sale of energy or provision for transmission services on either an hourly, daily, weekly or monthly basis (a "TRANSACTION") provided for herein can occur, shall commence on August 1, 1986, and shall continue until terminated by either Party upon giving the other Party no less than four (4) weeks prior written notice of termination. The applicable provisions of this AGREEMENT shall remain in effect after such termination to the extent necessary to provide for final billing, billing adjustments and payments. ARTICLE 2 - AVAILABILITY CRITERIA & OPERATION 2.1 The obligation of the Seller or Transmitter to supply the energy or transmission services is subordinate to and subject to its primary public service obligations, its firm contractual obligations, and obligations to its Pool. If, for any of these reasons, the Seller or Transmitter cannot make the energy or transmission service available, in whole or in part, at the price initially quoted, the Seller or Transmitter may cancel the TRANSACTION, or the schedule and charges may be modified as then agreed to by the Parties. In such event, the Buyer shall be obligated to pay only the energy charge and the energy reservation charge for the energy delivered during each hour of the TRANSACTION, or the transmission service charge for transmission service provided during each hour of the TRANSACTION. 2.2 In the event of unanticipated transmission constraints on the Buyer's system or in the Buyer's Pool which reduce the Buyer's ability to deliver energy to its load, the Buyer may cancel the TRANSACTION, or the schedule and charges may be modified as then agreed to with the Seller. In such event, the Buyer shall be obligated to pay only the energy charge and the energy reservation charge, or the transmission service charge, for the energy delivered during each hour of the TRANSACTION. 2.3 In addition to the reductions for transmission constraints detailed in paragraph 2.2, the Buyer shall be entitled to reduce, in whole or in part, the hourly deliveries from the Seller for any other reason during the period of the TRANSACTION. In the event of a reduction by the Buyer for any other reason, the Buyer shall not be obligated to pay the energy charge for any energy not delivered, but shall pay the full energy reservation charges as provided for in Sections 3.1.3 and 5.1.2. ARTICLE 3 - PURCHASE 3.1 Prior to each TRANSACTION involving the purchase of energy, the Parties shall determine and agree prior to the commencement of a TRANSACTION as to the following: 3.1.1 The amount of energy which can be purchased during the schedule period, expressed in megawatthours per hour. 3.1.2 The energy charge as provided for in section 5.1.1 expressed in dollars per megawatthour. 3.1.3 An energy reservation charge as provided for in Section 5.1.2. 3.1.4 Any specific transaction provision regarding cancellation, reduction rights and reserve considerations. 3.2 Prior to each TRANSACTION involving the provision of transmission services to or from others not a Party hereto, the Parties shall determine and agree prior to the commencement of such transactions to the following: 3.2.1 The Party to whom delivery is to be made, or from whom delivery is to be received. 3.2.2 The amount of energy to be delivered by the transmitting Party during the scheduled TRANSACTION period. 3.2.3 A transmission service charge as provided for in Section 5.2. ARTICLE 4 - NOTIFICATION OF TRANSACTIONS 4.1 NIAGARA MOHAWK shall notify the New York Power Pool (NYPP) and FE UTILITIES or MAIT, as appropriate, shall notify the Pennsylvania-New Jersey-Maryland Interconnection (PJM) when the first TRANSACTION will start. Thereafter, NIAGARA MOHAWK and FE UTILITIES or MAIT, as appropriate, shall notify NYPP and PJM respectively of the status and amount of each TRANSACTION as appropriate, prior to the commencement of the TRANSACTION. Instructions as to the exact procedure to be followed in giving all such notifications will be determined by agreement of the Parties and NYPP and PJM will be notified of such procedures. ARTICLE 5 - CHARGES 5.1 For TRANSACTIONS consisting of the purchase of energy made pursuant to Section 3.1 of this AGREEMENT, the Buyer shall pay to the Seller both an energy charge and an energy reservation charge for deliveries of energy. 5.1.1 The monthly energy charge shall be the sum of the hourly charges during the month deliveries were made, determined by multiplying (i) the megawatthours delivered by the Seller to the i3uyer during each hour of the billing month, by (ii) the agreed-upon energy charge rate expressed in dollars per megawatthour during each hour of the billing month as quoted by the Seller to the Buyer prior to entering into such TRANSACTION. 5.1.2 The monthly energy reservation charge shall be the sum of the products of multiplying the agreed-upon energy reservation charge rate for each TRANSACTION by the megawatthours scheduled in each TRANSACTION during the billing month unless modified by paragraph 2.1 or 2.2. The energy reservation charge rate for each TRANSACTION will be mutually agreed to by the Parties prior to each TRANSACTION, but in no event shall such charge exceed $32.20 per megawatthour when NIAGARA MOHAMK is the Seller, nor shall such charge exceed $32.20 per megawatthour when any of the FE UTILITIES is the Seller. Nothing contained herein shall be construed as affecting in any way the right of the Party, either Buyer or Seller, under this AGREEMENT to unilaterally make application to the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) for a change in the maximum energy reservation charge rate under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act and pursuant to the Commission's Rules and Regulations promulgated thereunder. 5.2 For TRANSACTIONS involving the provision of transmission services pursuant to Section 3.2 of this AGREEMENT, the Party requesting such services shall pay the Transmitter a transmission service charge base rate of $3.00 per megawatthour, which includes a provision for losses. In addition, the Transmitter may add a charge representing the Transmitter's unrealized savings from transactions forgone during the scheduled period of Transmission Services, as mutually agreed to by the Parties prior to the TRANSACTION. This additional charge shall not exceed $40.00 per megawatthour when Niagara Mohawk is the Transmitter or $40.00 per megawatthour when JCP&L or MAIT is the Transmitter. Nothing contained herein shall be construed as affecting in any way the right of either party hereto to unilaterally make application to the FERC for a change in the transmission service charge rate, under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act and pursuant to the Commission's Rules and Regulations promulgated thereunder. 5.3 The base rates for transmission service and the maximum amounts for additional charges may be updated on January 1 of each year. Any such updates shall be mutually agreed to by the Parties. 5.4 It is agreed that transactions under this Agreement will not adversely impact on payments made under Schedule 6.02 of the NYPP/PJM Agreement as such payments are calculated thereunder. ARTICLE 6 - BILLING AND PAYMENT 6.1 Bills shall be rendered by the Seller as soon as practicable after the end of each calendar month in which charges were incurred, and will be due and payable the later of (i) ten (10) days after receipt of the bill, or (ii) the first banking day common to the Parties following the 19th day of the month which the bill was rendered. Each bill shall incorporate such information as may be reasonably necessary to determine the payments due. Payments shall be made by wire transfer. Payment received after the due date will be charged interest from the due date until receipt at a daily rate equivalent to the prime annual lending rate plus one percentage point, such prime lending rate to be as determined by Citibank, N.A. at the time of such late payment. ARTICLE 7 - TRANSMISSION 7.1 All deliveries consequent to TRANSACTIONS hereunder shall be considered to be made at the points at which Buyer's and Seller's systems interconnect or at points where both Parties, through agreements with others, may be entitled to delivery or receipt of energy. ARTICLE 8 - LIABILITY 8.1 Neither Party shall be responsible to the other Party for any damages whatsoever, including damages resulting from the negligence of such Party, which may result from any interruption or failure of service, or deficiencies in the quality of service hereunder. It is the intent of this provision that such Party shall assume the risks of interruption, failure or deficiency in the quality or quantity of service on the system of the other caused by the hazards of the business to the same extent as if it were itself operating the other's system for the purpose of supplying itself with electricity. 8.2 In the event the Seller is prevented by some disability from furnishing Buyer with energy pursuant to this AGREEMENT, Seller shall use all reasonable diligence to remove such disability and to resume delivery of energy to Buyer. 8.3 Each Party will indemnify and save the other Party harmless from and against all costs and damage by reason of bodily injury, death or damage to property caused by or sustained on any of its own facilities as a result of performance under this AGREEMENT. However, each of the Parties shall be solely responsible for and shall bear all costs arising from any events, except those covered under the provisions of Article 8.1 above, caused by the actions of its own employees, contractors, or agents no matter where the event occurs. Each of the Parties shall be solely responsible for and shall bear all the costs of claims by its own employees, contractors, or agents arising under, and covered by, any Worker's Compensation law. Each of the Parties shall furnish, at its sole expense, such insurance coverage and such evidence thereof or evidence of self-insurance satisfactory to the other Party as the other Party may reasonably require with respect to its obligations under this Section. ARTICLE 9 - REGULATIONS, ORDERS, APPROVALS AND PERMITS 9.1 This AGREEMENT is made subject to present and future local, state and federal laws and to present and future regulations or order of any local, state or federal regulatory authority having jurisdiction over the matters set forth herein, and performance hereunder is conditioned upon securing and retaining such local, state or federal approvals, grants or permits as many from time-to-time be necessary with respect to such performance. All parties agree to use all reasonable efforts to secure and retain all such approvals, grants or permits. ARTICLE 10 - ASSIGNMENT 10.1 Recognizing that the number and timing of the TRANSACTIONS provided for herein are uncertain, it is agreed that this AGREEMENT and/or the rights of either Party under this AGREEMENT shall not be assigned, pledged or otherwise transferred without the prior written consent of the other Party except that either Party may assign or transfer its obligations under this AGREEMENT without obtaining such prior written consent if such assignment or transfer is either (i) incident to a merger, consolidation or acquisition of all, or substantially all, of the electric utility property or generating facilities of the transferor, or (ii) made to a Party's parent or wholly-owned subsidiary or to any utility which is under common ownership or control with it. Any such assignee or transferee shall be required to assume all the obligations of the assignor or transferor under this AGREEMENT. ARTICLE 11 - ACCOUNTS AND RECORDS 11.1 Seller or Transmitter shall keep complete and accurate records, meter readings and memoranda of its operations hereunder and shall maintain such data for a period of at least one (1) year after each TRANSACTION. Buyer shall have the right to examine and inspect all such records, meter readings and memoranda insofar as may be necessary for the purpose of ascertaining the reasonableness and accuracy of all relevant data, estimates or statement of charges submitted to all hereunder. ARTICLE 12 - INTERPRETATION 12.1 The interpretation and performance of this AGREEMENT shall be in accordance with and shall be controlled by the laws of the State of New York. ARTICLE 13 - MISCELLANEOUS 13.1 Each Party shall prepare, execute and deliver to the other Party any documents reasonably required to implement any provision hereof. 13.2 Any number of counterparts of this AGREEMENT may be executed and each shall have the same force and effect as the original. 13.3 This AGREEMENT shall constitute the entire understanding between the Parties and shall supersede any and all previous understandings pertaining to the subject matter of this AGREEMENT. 13.4 This AGREEMENT may be modified only by an instrument in writing signed by the Parties hereto. IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have caused this AGREEMENT to be signed by their respective duly authorized representatives as of the date first above written. NIAGARA MOHAWK POWER CORPORATION BY: FE COMPANIES BY: SUPPLEMENTAL AGREEMENT This SUPPLEMENTAL AGREEMENT, made as of the 14th day of April, 1987, by and between Niagara Mohawk Power Corporation and Jersey Central Power & Light Company (JCP&L), Metropolitan Edison Company, and Pennsylvania Electric Company (collectively, FE Utilities), and Mid-Atlantic Interstate Transmission, LLC (MAIT) (together with FE Utilities, FE Companies). NIAGARA MOHAWK POWER CORPORATION BY: FE COMPANIES BY: SECOND SUPPLEMENTAL AGREEMENT This SECOND SUPPLEMENTAL AGREEMENT, made as of the 8th day of February, 1988, by and between Niagara Mohawk Power Corporation ("Niagara Mohawk") and Jersey Central Power & Light Company (JCP&L), Metropolitan Edison Company, and Pennsylvania Electric Company (collectively, "FE Utilities"), and Mid-Atlantic Interstate Transmission, LLC ("MAIT")(together with FE Utilities, "FE Companies"). WITNESSETH THAT: WHEREAS, the signatories hereto are signatories to a Purchase and Sale Agreement ("AGREEMENT"), dated July 1, 1986; and WHEREAS, the Agreement was filed with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("Commission") as a rate schedule under the Federal Power Act ("Act"); and WHEREAS, on March 18, 1987, the Commission issued an Order Accepting Agreement for Filing with Suspension in Part and Without Suspension in Part (38 FERC Paragraph 61,175), which among other things se., for hearing the issues of (i) the appropriate ceiling for the energy reservation charge and (ii) the effects of the transaction conducted pursuant to the Agreement on the facilities of New York State Electric & Gas Corporation ("NYSEG"); WHEREAS, the AGREEMENT was amended by a SUPPLEMENTAL AGREEMENT, dated April 14, 1987, which Supplemental Agreement was accepted by the Commission by an Order, dated September 16, 1987, and WHEREAS, the parties to the proceeding initiated by the Commission's Order of March 18, 1987 have by agreements resolved the issues set for hearing by that Order, which agreements were reflected in Offers of Partial Settlement that were filed with the Commission and were accepted by the Commission as evidenced by the letter, dated January 21, 1988 of the Acting Secretary of the Commission; and WHEREAS, it is the purpose of this Second Supplemental Agreement to amend the AGREEMENT to give effect to the aforementioned Offers of Partial Settlement which are hereby incorporated in this Second Supplemental agreement. NOW, THEREFORE, the signatories hereto agrees as follows: SECTION I - Section 5.1.2 of the AGREEMENT shall be, and is hereby, amended by substituting the figure "$19" for the figure $32.20" in the second sentence of Section 5.1.2 so that such sentence reads as follows: "The energy reservation charge rate for each TRANSACTION will be mutually agreed to by the Parties prior to each TRANSACTION, but in no event shall such charge exceed $19 per megawatthour when NIAGARA MOHAWK is the Seller, nor shall such charge exceed $19 per megawatthour when any of the FE Utilities is the Seller." SECTION II - The Agreement shall be, and is hereby, amended by adding new Sections 5.5 and 5.6 providing as follows: 5.5 In no event shall the hourly transactions pursuant to the Agreement exceed 500 MW. This Second Supplemental Agreement, however, is in no way intended to either diminish or increase FE Companies' or Niagara Mohawk's rights under the Federal Power Act, 16 U.S.C. Section 824 et seq. (1982)), or the Commission's regulations, 18 C.F.R. Pt. 1 et seq. (1987), to make the appropriate filing with the Commission to effect a change of the 500 MW cap. 5.6 In no event shall the net simultaneous deliveries from MAIT or Niagara Mohawk, pursuant to any and all agreements, utilizing the contract path exceed the seasonal normal rating of the contract path, as shown on Schedule 1 attached hereto and made a part hereof, and in no event shall the sum of the absolute magnitudes of the simultaneous deliveries exceed twice the seasonal normal capability of the contract path. This Second Supplemental Agreement, however, is in no way intended to either diminish or increase FE Companies' or Niagara Mohawk's rights under the Federal Power Act, 16 U.S.C. Section 824 et seq. (1982, or the Commission's regulations, 18 C.F.R. Pt. 1 et seq. (1987), to change the contract path or contract path facilities, the interconnecting facilities of and between FE Companies and Niagara Mohawk, or enter into new agreements which utilize the contract path. SECTION III - All other terms and conditions of the July 1, 1986 AGREEMENT, and the April 14, 1987 SUPPLEMENTAL AGREEMENT, shall remain in full force and effect. SECTION IV - This SECOND SUPPLEMENT AGREEMENT shall become effective on February 8, 1988 or at such other date as may be allowed by the Federal energy Regulatory Commission. IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the Parties have caused this AGREEMENT to be signed by their duly authorized representatives as of the date first above written. SCHEDULE 6.02 INTERCONNECTION AGREEMENT BETWEEN THE NYPP GROUP AND THE PJM GROUP Issued: September 5, 1985 Effective: May 1, 1984 UNSCHEDULED TRANSMISSION SERVICES Section 1.09 of this Agreement provides that the parties of the NYPP GROUP and the parties of the PJM GROUP shall not intentionally use each other's facilities except as provided in the Agreement. Transmission services associated with transactions scheduled directly between the Groups such as Economy Energy, Supplemental Service, Conservation Energy and Non-Replacement Energy are provided for in other Schedules specifically describing such transactions. Transmission services provided by either Group for the other in connection with transactions not scheduled directly or otherwise prearranged between the Groups shall be defined and compensated for in accordance with this Schedule. Section 1 - Definition of Service Whenever either Group arranges energy transactions other than those scheduled directly or otherwise prearranged between the Groups and all or part of such energy flows on the transmission system of the other Group in such magnitude as to impose economic detriment on said other Group and its customers, such other Group shall be deemed to have provided Unscheduled Transmission Service under the terms of this Schedule. The flow on the Branchburg-Ramapo 500 KV line shall be deemed to be the measure of flow between the Groups. The metered flow on that line shall be adjusted each hour by factors determined by the NYPP-PJM Operating Committee to equal the flow which would have occurred if any and all of the following had not occurred: a) NYPP-PJM scheduled energy transactions; b) Scheduled transmission service by either Group for the other Group; c) Imbalance in the energy transfer by NYPP across the system of the Public Service Electric and Gas Company; d) Unusual transactions by others not party to this agreement, as determined by the NYPP-PJM Operating Committee. The amount each hour by which the adjusted metered flow exceeds 400 MW in either direction on that line shall constitute the amount of Unscheduled Transmission Service provided to the Group whose energy transactions cause the excess flow. Excess flows caused by interregional emergencies shall be excluded from the determination of Unscheduled Transmission Service. The Group providing such Unscheduled Transmission Service shall furnish or make available to the other Group all information necessary to determine the amount of such Service provided. Section 2 - Compensation Whenever Unscheduled Transmission Service as defined in Section 1 is provided by either Group during the period May 1, 1984, through June 30, 1985, the Group receiving the service shall compensate the other Group by providing such other Group equivalent amounts, as increased below, of transmission service availability in comparable hours of operation after the in-service date of a Phase Angle Regulator to be installed at Ramapo. Whenever Unscheduled Transmission Service as defined in Section 1 is provided by either Group during the period beginning July 1, 1985, and terminating on the in-service date of the Phase Angle Regulator to be installed at Ramapo, the compensation payable by the Group receiving the service shall be determined each hour as the amount of such service multiplied by a rate calculated as the difference between the actual hourly average cost of generation operated by the other Group as a result of providing the service and the average cost in that hour of more economical power available to the other Group from other members of its Group or from systems not party to this Agreement which could have been utilized but for the Unscheduled Transmission Service provided, except that in any month the dollar compensation shall be 50% of the total due in that month but limited to the amount needed to make the cumulative average monthly compensation paid equal to $2.5 million. Compensation due in excess of the dollar amount paid each month shall to paid by providing the other Group equivalent amounts, as increased below, of transmission service availability in comparable hours of operation after the in-service date of the Phase Angle Regulator to be installed at Ramapo. The foregoing amounts of transmission service availability compensation shall be provided under operating procedures determined by the NYPP-PJM Operating Committee based on the amounts of Unscheduled Transmission Service as defined in Section 1 increased by a factor of: 1.15 if such compensation is deferred up to 36 months, 1.20 if deferred more than 36 but less than 50 months, and 1.25 if deferred 50 months or more. Whenever Unscheduled Transmission Service as defined in Section 1 is provided by either Group subsequent to the in-service date of the Phase Angle Regulator to be installed at Ramapo, the compensation payable by the Group receiving the service shall be determined each hour by the amount of such service multiplied by a rate calculated as the difference between the actual hourly average cost of generation operated by the other Group as a result of providing the service and the average cost in that hour of more economical power available to the other Group from other members of the Group or from systems not party to this Agreement which could have been utilized but for the Unscheduled Transmission Service provided. Initially, and until otherwise determined by the NYPP-PJM Operating Committee, the maximum value of the compensation rate shall be $40 per megawatthour. It is intended that compensation by transmission service availability shall be completed by December 31, 1991. In the event that compensation by transmission service availability cannot be completed by December 31, 1991, alternative compensation will be determined by the NYPP/PJM Operating Committee. Monthly dollar compensation shall be due and payable in accordance with Article 4 - Billing Procedure. The Group providing Unscheduled Transmission Service shall furnish or make available to the other Group all information necessary to determine the dollar amount to be paid and the transmission service availability to be provided. THIRD SUPPLEMENTAL AGREEMENT This THIRD SUPPLEMENTAL AGREEMENT is made as of the 1st day of January, 1995 by and between Niagara Mohawk Power Corporation (Niagara Mohawk) and Jersey Central Power & Light Company (JCP&L), Metropolitan Edison Company, and Pennsylvania Electric Company (collectively, FE Utilities), and Mid-Atlantic Interstate Transmission, LLC (MAIT) (together with FE Utilities, FE Companies). WHEREAS, the signatories hereto are signatories to an Agreement (AGREEMENT), dated July 1, 1986, known as the Purchase and Sale Agreement, and WHEREAS, it is desired to amend the AGREEMENT to clarify the method of determining the energy charge rate of the Seller. NOW, THEREFORE, the signatories hereto agree as follows: Section I - The AGREEMENT shall be and is hereby amended by inserting the following at the end of Article 5.1.1: The cost of emissions allowances shall be included in the forecasted incremental cost to the Seller of providing the energy. The replacement cost of emissions allowances will be used to recover the cost of emissions allowances consumed as a result of producing energy supplied to the other Party. Each Party will determine its replacement cost of emissions allowances, such cost to be an amount not exceeding the market price index published by Cantor-Fitzgerald Environmental Brokerage Services ("CFEBS") or, in the event CFEBS ceases publishing its index, an index approved by the parties. As with other components of cost required for accounting, each Party will use the same replacement cost of emissions allowances, so determined, as it uses for coordinating operation of its generating facilities hereunder. For each party, the cost of emissions allowances is included in the cost of energy supplied under this Agreement. The quantity of emissions allowances associated with a sale by FE Utilities will be determined using an "Emissions per MWhr factor," calculated as the forecasted annual emissions from FE Utilities Phase I units (in tons of SO2) divided by the forecasted annual total energy produced by FE Utilities (in MWhr). The Emissions per MWhr factor (in tons of SO2 per MWhr) will be multiplied by the magnitude of the transaction (in MWhr) to determine the emissions allowances associated with the transaction (in tons of SO2). If the calculated number of allowances used includes a fraction of an allowance, the amount will be rounded up to the next whole number if the fraction is one-half or greater, or rounded down if the fraction is less than one-half. The total cost of emissions allowances associated with a sale by FE Utilities will be determined using a "Charge per MWhr factor," calculated as the sum of FE Utilities' forecasted annual emissions (in tons of SO2), multiplied by its emissions allowance replacement cost (in dollars per ton of SO2), which sum shall be divided by the forecasted annual total energy produced by FE Utilities (in MWhr). The Charge per MWhr factor (in dollars per MWhr) will be multiplied by the magnitude of the transaction (in MWhr) to determine the cost of the emission allowances (in dollars) associated with the transaction. The quantity of emissions allowances associated with a sale by NIAGARA MOHAWK will be determined based on the fuel consumption and emissions information of the relevant generating unit(s) or station(s). The parties waive their right to payment-in-kind for emissions allowances for transactions under this Agreement. Cash payments shall be transferred in accordance with the billing provisions of Article 8. Section II - All other terms and conditions of the July 1, 1986 AGREEMENT shall remain in full force and effect. Section III - This Third Supplemental Agreement shall become effective on January 1, 1995, or at such other date as may be allowed by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.

Jersey Central Power & Light Company and Mid-Atlantic Interstate Transmission, LLC are hereinafter sometimes referred to collectively as the "Parties" or individually as a "Party". WHEREAS, the Parties hereto are subsidiaries of FirstEnergy Corporation, and their bulk power obligations are planned and operated as an Integrated System, with resulting advantages of reliability and economy accruing to the public served by them; and WHEREAS, the Parties agree that recent changes in the electric industry coupled with the voluntary divestitures of their generating facilities require the Parties to amend and restate the 1969 Agreement in its entirety; and WHEREAS, the Integrated System is operated on a coordinated basis as part of the PJM Interconnection L.L.C. ("PJM") under the terms of the PJM Operating Agreement dated June 2, 1997 as revised. NOW, THEREFORE, THIS AGREEMENT WITNESSETH, that in consideration of the premises and of the mutual covenants and conditions hereinafter set forth, the Parties hereto do hereby covenant and agree with each other as follows: ARTICLE I Subject: Definitions As used in this Agreement: 1.1 Accounted-For Obligation - shall have the meaning set forth in Schedule 1.02. 1.2 Active Load Management or "ALM" - shall mean active load management in accordance with Schedule 1.04. 1.3 ALM Factor - shall mean that factor approved from time to time by the Reliability Committee for use in the determination of credit for ALM in accordance with Schedule 1.04. 1.4 Capacity Resources - shall mean megawatts of net capacity from owned or contracted for generating facilities which are accredited to a Party and are committed to satisfy that Party's obligations under this Agreement. 1.5 Integrated System - shall mean the interconnected electric supply system of the Parties hereto. 1.6 Load - shall mean an amount of megawatt hours integrated during a clock-hour, and when used as a measure of a system's energy requirements shall mean net load, exclusive of generating station auxiliaries and lighting. 1.7 Load Serving Entity or LSE - shall mean any entity (or the duly designated agent of such an entity), including a load aggregator or power marketer, (i) serving end-users within the PJM Control Area, and (ii) that has been granted the authority or has an obligation pursuant to state or local law, regulation or franchise to sell electric energy to end-users located within the PJM Control Area. 1.8 Market Price of Unforced Capacity - shall mean the weighted average price of Unforced Capacity credits in each of the PJM capacity auctions for a day. 1.9 Monthly Size Factor - shall mean the ratio of the Load of a Party summed over a month to the Load of the Integrated system summed over a month. 1.10 Operating Capacity - shall mean the amount of generating capacity scheduled to be available for a specified period of an operating day to ensure the reliable operation of the PJM Control Area, as specified in the PJM Manuals. 1.11 PJM Capacity Deficiency Charges - shall mean charges by PJM to GPU under the Reliability Assurance Agreement for capacity deficiencies of GPU. 1.12 PJM Capacity Deficiency Payments - shall mean payments by PJM to GPU under the Reliability Assurance Agreement for capacity deficiencies of others. 1.13 PJM Control Area - shall mean that certain control area encompassing systems in Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Maryland, Delaware and the District of Columbia and which is recognized by the North American Electric Reliability Council ("NERC") as the PJM Control Area. 1.14 PJM Office of Interconnection - ARTICLE II Interconnections to be Made Available SECTION 1. The Parties hereto shall continue to make available the existing transmission interconnections between their respective systems and such other facilities as are required for the reliable operation of the Integrated System. SECTION 2. By mutual agreement and as may be required from time to time, consistent with Good Utility Practice, the Parties hereto shall make future additional expenditures to improve the interconnection transmission lines and facilities, as well as to construct and to make available additional interconnection transmission lines and facilities. ARTICLE III Service to be Rendered SECTION 1. In order to obtain the maximum benefits of interconnected operation, the amount and source of any purchased energy and/or capacity, or the utilization of any remaining generating facilities, shall be determined on a basis which is most economical for the systems of the individual Parties as well as for the Integrated System, giving due consideration to the maintenance of proper and adequate service to the customers of each of the individual Parties. SECTION 2. To equalize the future benefits and burdens related to the purchase of energy and/or capacity, it is the intent that each Party hereto shall provide a share, approximately proportional to its expected customer load, of the Integrated System. To provide such share a Party may individually or in association with other Parties hereto purchase from others not Parties hereto, or may make short-term purchases from Parties hereto. The amount and duration of such short-term purchases shall be determined from time to time after the effective date of this Agreement in accordance with the terms and conditions set forth in the applicable schedules attached hereto. SECTION 3. As a result of the provisions for the purchase of energy and/or capacity on a forecast basis, individual Parties will at times be deficient in energy and/or capacity, and payments shall be made by such Party or Parties to the other Party or Parties in compensation for excess energy and/or capacity supplied by them to the deficient Parties. The methods of measuring the amount of such deficiency in or excess of energy and/or capacity, and the methods of determining the rates and charges are set forth in the applicable schedules attached hereto. SECTION 4. The Parties hereto, when it is to their mutual advantage or when one or more Parties can provide energy and/or capacity at a lower cost than the other Party or Parties, shall sell to and purchase from each other, or interchange energy and/or capacity, and the methods of determining the rates and charges therefor are set forth in the applicable schedules and attached hereto. SECTION 5. Energy and/or capacity transactions may also occur between the Parties acting as a group and other interconnected systems. The methods of allocation of credits and charges resulting from such transactions are set forth in the applicable schedules attached hereto. SECTION 6. To equalize the future benefits and burdens related to the planned installation of the bulk transmission system, it is the intent that each Party hereto shall provide or be financially responsible for a share of the system, approximately proportional to its expected benefit derived from the planned bulk transmission facilities of the Integrated System. In the determination of appropriate shares, as required by this section, consideration shall be given not only to the ownership of such facilities, but also to (a) payments made or received under this Agreement; (b) payments made or received under agreements with others; and (c) relative costs for comparable facilities as influenced by location or time of construction. Imbalance among the relative contributions shall be corrected by payments among the Parties as set forth in the applicable schedules attached hereto. ARTICLE IV Operation SECTION 1. The energy to be supplied hereunder shall be in the form of three-phase, sixty-cycle alternating current at a nominal voltage at each delivery point approximately equal to the voltage rating of the particular transmission line interconnections mentioned in Article II hereof. SECTION 2. Each Party shall adjust, maintain and operate the portion of the interconnection facilities made available by it in accordance with good utility practice and in such a manner as will render, to the greatest extent practicable and reasonable, the services intended hereunder, and shall from time to time make such replacement and renewals as may be required to insure the good operating condition of such facilities. Each Party shall adjust, maintain and operate the remainder of its system in accordance with good utility practice and in such manner as will, to the extent practicable and reasonable, protect the apparatus and circuits of the others from damage and interruption by lightning, short circuits, potential surges, or otherwise and prevent any disturbance or condition originating in its system from affecting service in the systems of the other Parties. SECTION 3. Estimates of customer load shall be provided by the Parties as often as shall be required to maintain satisfactory operation of the Integrated System, and any and all system records and accounts pertaining thereto shall be made available at reasonable times by all Parties to each other. ARTICLE V Points of Delivery The points of delivery of electric energy supplied hereunder shall be the points of connection of the transmission facilities between the Parties hereto. ARTICLE VI Metering SECTION 1. All energy flow between the transmission and distribution systems of the Parties hereto shall be measured by means of suitable metering equipment as now existing or as hereafter mutually agreed upon. SECTION 2. All metering equipment used under this Agreement may be inspected or tested by qualified representatives of any of the Parties hereto at such times as may be mutually agreed upon, SECTION 3. Procedure in respect to maintenance, testing, calibrating, correction and registration records and precision tolerances of all metering equipment used under this Agreement shall be in accordance with good utility practice and as may be agreed upon among the Parties hereto from time to time. ARTICLE VI Indemnity Each Party hereto shall save harmless the other Parties hereto of and from any and all loss and damage by reasons of any bodily injury, death, or damage to property caused or sustained in that part of the interconnection facilities owned, controlled or made available by it, notwithstanding that a judgment may be rendered against one or all of the other Parties hereto; except that each Party hereto shall be responsible for all claims of its own employees , agents and servants growing out of any workmen's compensation law ARTICLE VIII Authority SECTION 1. A Vice President of the Parties is hereby authorized to file with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC") on behalf of all the Parties hereto, this Agreement, amendments or supplements made by them to this Agreement, and revised schedules, prepared by them to replace those attached to and made a part of this Agreement. On or before the seventh working day of each month MAIT shall prepare or cause to be prepared statements for all transactions under this Agreement which occurred during the preceding month. Payments of the net amounts due shall be made directly among the Parties hereto on or before the twentieth day of the month. SECTION 2. The monthly amounts owed to or due from PJM or others, and which are to be allocated under the terms of this Agreement, shall be so allocated among the Parties hereto. MAIT shall make timely collection of such amounts and either deliver them to PJM, or to others as appropriate, or distribute them among the Parties hereto. The responsibility for capacity, equal in total to the Unforced Capacity of the Integrated System shall be allocated among the Parties by application of the methods specified in the PJM Reliability Assurance Agreement (RAA). Those Parties that are deficient in capacity shall make payments to those Parties having excess capacity for each megawatt of deficiency. The pricing for these transactions will be based on the capacity cost of the Parties having excess. The cost will be the acquisition cost for system bilateral and market auction purchases and the Market Price of Unforced Capacity for company specific capacity including owned capacity, Non-Utility Generators ("NUGS") and company specific bilateral purchases. Each Party shall sell from its portfolio starting with the highest cost capacity. SUBJECT: DETERMINATIONS OF ACCOUNTED FOR OBLIGATIONS AND DEFICIENCIES A. Each Party's Accounted-For Obligation shall be determined pursuant to the provisions of this Section A. 1. For each billing month during a Planning Period up to and including the month in which the peak load for the PJM Control Area during the summer period is known, the Account-For Obligation of a Party shall be determined, for the Zone in which the Party is serving load, on a daily basis as follows: Accounted-For Obligation = {(FSP x DF) - ALM} x FPR/100 Where: FSP = the daily summation of the weather-adjusted actual coincident summer peak for the previous summer of the end-users for which the Party was responsible on that billing day, as determined in accordance with the procedures set forth in the PJM Manuals DF = the Diversity Factor of the combined GPU Zone ALM = the ALM load credits of the Party for the Zone determined pursuant to Schedule 1.04 for the previous summer as applicable to the end-users for which the Party was responsible on that billing day. FPR = the Forecast Pool Requirement The total Accounted-For Obligation of a Party shall be the sum of that Party's Accounted-For Obligations in the Zones in which the Party is serving load. 2. Beginning in the billing month following the month in which the peak load for the PJM Control Area during the summer period is known, the Accounted-For Obligation of a Party shall be determined for the remaining months of the Planning Period, for the Zone in which the Party is serving the load, on a daily basis, as follows: Accounted-For Obligation = {(ASP x DF) - ALM} x FPR/100 Where: ASP = the daily summation of the weather-adjusted actual coincident summer peak load of the end-users for which the Party was responsible on that billing day, as determined in accordance with the procedures set forth in the PJM Manuals. DF = the Diversity Factor for the combined GPU Zone ALM = the ALM load credits of the Party for the Zone determined pursuant to Schedule 1.04 as applicable to the end-users for which the Party was responsible on that billing day. FPR = the Forecast Pool Requirement The total Accounted-For Obligation of a Party shall be the sum of that Party's Accounted-For Obligations in each of the Zones in which the Party is serving load. This Accounted-For Obligation, before increases from 4a below, shall be the Load-Based Obligation. 3. External purchases and sales of Unforced Capacity will be allocated as follows: a. Assign purchases or sales which are contractually specific to a GPU Company. b. Allocate GPU bilateral sales in proportion to each GPUE Company's expected excess above its Load-based Obligation. c. Allocate GPU Market Auction Sales in proportion to each GPUE Company's expected excess above its Load-based Obligation. d. Allocate GPU bilateral purchases in proportion to each GPUE Company's expected Load-based Capacity Deficiency. e. Allocate GPU Market Auction Purchases in proportion to each GPUE Company's expected Load-based Capacity Deficiency. 4. For each day, the total Unforced Capacity of the Parties, after adjustment for external purchases and sales, will be compared to the sum of the Accounted-For Obligations of each of the Parties. a. If the total Unforced Capacity is greater than the sum of the Accounted-For obligations, the Accounted-For Obligations of the Parties shall be proportionately increased to equal the total Unforced Capacity. These increased obligations shall be referenced to hereafter as the "Capacity-Based Obligations". The Party(s) with Unforced Capacity in excess of their Capacity-Based Obligation shall sell it to the Party(s) which is deficient at the prices stated in Schedule 1.01 C. The Parties will share Capacity Deficiency Payments from PJM in proportion to their Accounted-For Obligation. b. If the total Unforced Capacity is less than the sum of the Accounted-For Obligations, any Party with Unforced Capacity in excess of its Accounted-For Obligation shall sell it to those Parties which are deficient in proportion to their deficiency at the prices stated in Schedule 1.01 C. The deficient Parties would proportionately pay the PJM Capacity Deficiency charges. B. For purposes of determining deficiencies pursuant to paragraphs A.3 and A.4 of this Schedule, the sum of the Unforced Capacity for each Capacity Resource utilized by a Party shall be established by the PJM Office of the Interconnection on a daily basis, subject only to adjustment for the transfer of rights to Capacity Resources during a period in the initial billing month (as defined in the PJM Manuals) in which the final Accounted-For Obligation of a Party is known; provided, however, that such transfers of rights to Capacity Resources shall (1) include only resources that qualify as Capacity Resources on the day a Party intends to rely on the Unforced Capacity of those Capacity Resources to satisfy its Accounted-For Obligation and (2) exclude any Firm Transmission Rights, as that term is defined under the Operating Agreement. SUBJECT: FORCED OUTAGE RATE CALCULATION A. The equivalent demand forced outage rate ("EFORD") shall be calculated as follows: EFORD (%) = [{ff * FOH + fp * EFPOH) / (SH + Ff * FOH}] * 100 Where: Ff = full outage factor Fp = partial outage factor FOH = full forced outage hours EFPOH = equivalent forced partial outage hours SH = service hours Calculations of average EFORD for Accounted-For Obligations concerning Unforced Capacity: The average EFORD used to determine a Load Serving Entity's ability to meet its Accounted-For Obligation for Unforced Capacity in a month shall be the average of the forced outage rates, weighted for unit capability, calculated on a twelve-month rolling average basis for the twelve-month period ending two months prior to the month for which the obligation was incurred, attributable to all of the generating units of the Load Serving Entity committed to serve load within the Zone. These resources include Capacity Resources purchased from specified units and exclude Capacity Resources sold from specified units. Such rate shall also include (i) an adjustment, if any, for capacity unavailable due to energy limitations determined in accordance with definitions and criteria set forth in the PJM Manuals and (ii) any other adjustments approved by the PJM Reliability Committee to adjust the parameters of a designated unit. 2. The EFORD of a unit in service twelve or more full calendar months prior to the calculation month shall be the average rate experienced by such unit during the twelve most recent calendar months, allowing for up to a two month period to collect data and calculate rates. Historical data shall be based on official reports of the Parties under rules and practices set forth in the PJM Manuals. 3. The EFORD of a unit in service at least one full calendar month but less than twelve full calendar months prior to the calculation month shall be the average of the actual EFORD experienced by the unit weighted by full months of service, and the class average rate for units with that capability and of that type weighted by twelve minus months of service, allowing for up to a two-month period to collect data and calculate rates. Historical data shall be based on official reports of the Parties under rules and practices set forth in the PJM Manuals. SUBJECT: PROCEDURES FOR THE ACTIVE LOAD MANAGEMENT CREDIT A. The procedures for Active Load Management Credit shall be determined by methods specified in the PJM Reliability Assurance Agreement (RAA). Modifications of schedules in the RAA, appropriate for application within the Integrated System, are included in this agreement. SUBJECT: PEAK SEASON MAINTENANCE A. To preserve and maintain the reliability of the PJM Control Area and to recognize the impact of planned outages and maintenance outages during the Peak Season, each Party is obligated to have sufficient Unforced Capacity to satisfy its Accounted-For Obligation plus its Peak Season Maintenance Obligation during the Peak Season. B. The Peak Season shall be defined to be those weeks containing the 24th through 36th Wednesdays of the calendar year. Each such week shall begin on a Monday and end on the following Sunday, except for the week containing the 36th Wednesday, which shall end on the following Friday. C. Peak Season Maintenance is defined as planned outages and maintenance outages during the Peak Season. D. For each day during the Peak Season, the Peak Season Maintenance Obligation of a Party shall be the amount, in megawatts, which shall be based on the Unforced Capacity of the Unit, of that Party's Peak Season Maintenance at the time of the PJM Control Area daily peak, excluding outages for maintenance when released by the Office of the Interconnection for a specified period and other outages as approved by the Reliability Committee from time to time. E. Peak Season Maintenance shall be added to the Accounted-For Obligation of the Party which has credit for the Unit. SUBJECT: INTERCHANGE ENERGY TRANSACTIONS AND CHARGES A. Interchange Energy Transactions represent the exchange of energy between the Parties that results from the coordinated operation of the Integrated System. B. The energy interchange among the Parties hereto is the result of (a) overall economic operation as modified at times by transmission limitations, the need for emergency supplies and area protection and (b) PJM accounting that retains for use of the GPU Group the lowest cost GPU Group energy available for such use. The net amount of interchange energy supplied or received by each party hereto shall be determined hourly. These amounts are the residuals required to balance each party's hourly net load with its net generation and net receipts, after accounting for firm supplies to or from others, and for energy amounts associated with other capacity supplies provided under Article III, Section 2 of this Agreement. C. The Party(s) supplying interchange energy for use by other Parties hereto shall be paid their respective Locational Marginal Price, as determined by PJM in accordance with the PJM Operating Agreement. D. For the purpose of pricing interchange, when there is more than one supplier of interchange within any hour (including both PJM and the Parties hereto), each receipt of interchange shall be considered to be from all suppliers in amounts proportional to the available supplies. The resulting average charge per megawatt-hour, shall be the same to each of the Parties hereto that is receiving interchange during that hour. SUBJECT: ALLOCATION OF PJM 500 kV SYSTEM LOSSES A. The losses on the 500 kV transmission systems in PJM assigned to GPU shall be allocated among the Parties in proportion to their load in the hour. B. Each Party's allocated losses shall be added to its load on an hour-by-hour basis, and a corresponding adjustment shall be made in its net interchange. SUBJECT: ALLOCATION OF PAYMENTS TO OR FROM PJM FOR TRANSMISSION CONGESTION CHARGES A. Transmission Congestion Charges are charges attributable to the increased cost of energy delivered at a given load bus where the transmission system serving that load bus is operating under constrained conditions. B. Each Party shall be responsible for its allocated share of payments to or from PJM for transmission congestion charges. A Party's allocated share shall be determined by allocating the total PJM payment to the Party in proportion to its allocator(A). (A) shall be determined each hour and shall equal (L - S - GI - PI), where: C. (L) equals the Party's total effective load cost, which shall be determined by multiplying the Party's total load plus bilateral sales in the hour by its weighted average Locational Marginal Price (LMP) for the hour. D. (S) equals the Party's total supply value, including owned generation and bilateral purchases, which shall be determined by multiplying the sum, for each supply source, of the supply in the hour by the LMP in the hour at the source of the supply. E. (GI) equals the Party's cost of interchange from the GPU Group, which shall be determined each hour in accordance with Schedule 2.01. F. (PI) equals the Party's cost of interchange from PJM, which shall be determined each hour in accordance with Schedule 3.01. SUBJECT: ALLOCATION OF PAYMENTS TO OR FROM PJM FOR TRANSMISSION CONGESTION CREDITS 1. Payments from PJM for transmission congestion credits will be allocated to the party whose load bus is specified in the Fixed Transmission Right which is the source of the transmission congestion credit. 2. Payments to PJM for negative transmission congestion credits will be the responsibility of the party whose load bus is specified in the Fixed Transmission Right which is the source of the negative transmission congestion credit. SUBJECT: ALLOCATIONS RELATED TO BILATERAL TRANSACTIONS A. Bilateral purchases made by GPUS on behalf of a party, and their associated costs, will be allocated to that party. B. Bilateral purchases made by GPUS on behalf of all Parties, and their associated costs, will be allocated to the Parties in proportion to their load in each hour of the transaction. C. Bilateral sales made by GPUS on behalf of a party, and their associated revenues, will be allocated to that party. D. Bilateral sales made by GPUS on behalf of all Parties, and their associated revenues, will be allocated to the Parties in proportion to their load in each hour of the transaction. E. Bilateral sales made by a Party to another Party shall be priced at a rate equal to the lowest price payable by the purchasing Party to a non-affiliated seller at the time a bilateral sale is negotiated. SUBJECT: ALLOCATION OF PAYMENTS TO OR FROM PJM FOR OPERATING CAPACITY AND ENERGY TRANSACTIONS A. The reserve operating capacity obligations of the GPU Group, including spinning, scheduled or other classifications of reserve are determined under the PJM Agreement. For all operating capacity or energy supplied by PJM to the GPU Group, full payments shall be made by the receiving Party or Parties. AMENDED LOAD SERVING ENTITY AGREEMENT BETWEEN METROPOLITAN EDISON COMPANY, CALPINE ENERGY SOLUTIONS, LLC AND ALLEGHENY ELECTRIC COOPERATIVE, INC. This Amended Load Serving Entity Agreement (“Agreement”) sets forth the agreement between Metropolitan Edison Company (doing business and hereafter referred to as “FirstEnergy”), Calpine Energy Solutions, LLC (“Calpine”) and Allegheny Electric Cooperative, Inc. (“AEC”) (collectively the “Parties” or individually a “Party”) in connection with Calpine becoming the Load Serving Entity (“LSE”), as said term is defined and utilized in the PJM Reliability Assurance Agreement, for the customer described in Attachment A hereto (“Customer”). The Parties, through their duly authorized representatives and intending to be legally bound hereby, agree as follows: 01. Calpine intends to sell power to the Customer pursuant to a certain power sales agreement with the Customer, and thus will become the LSE for said Customer. Calpine acknowledges and accepts the operational and financial responsibilities and obligations of a Supplier as set forth in this Agreement and in the FirstEnergy Procedure Manuals (BB: Supplier Peak Load Share Methodology (for Capacity and Transmission Obligation Purposes)) Commencing January 1, 2006 and Determination of Supplier Total Hourly Energy Obligation Commencing June 1, 1999, collectively the “Manuals” or individually a “Manual”) and in any amendments to the Manuals. The Manuals, the provisions of which are incorporated herein by reference, are as of the date of this Agreement, located within the Pennsylvania Supplier Registration section of the FirstEnergy website. 02. FirstEnergy shall calculate the energy, capacity and transmission values of the Customer Loads (collectively the “Customer Loads” or individually a “Customer Load”) in accordance with the Manuals. 03. A 1.021 loss factor shall be used in determining the Customer Loads. 04. Prior to the first day of energy delivery, Calpine shall be a full member of PJM. 05. FirstEnergy will continue to own and maintain the meters for the purpose of measuring Customer’s consumption. 06. FirstEnergy will own and have direct access to the meter and therefore the data necessary for measuring Customer’s consumption. In the event that the necessary meter data is unavailable for submittal to PJM in a timely fashion by FirstEnergy, FirstEnergy shall use estimating techniques in accordance with the Manuals. 07. FirstEnergy shall report to both PJM and Calpine the hourly Customer Load via a separate PJM energy schedule contract for the Customer. The energy schedule contract will use the MetEd Zone as the source and sink. 08. FirstEnergy shall report to AEC the hourly Customer Load as reported to PJM through the energy schedule contract. 09. FirstEnergy will report the Customer capacity peak load share and the Customer transmission peak load share to PJM, Calpine, and AEC. 10. The hourly Customer Load as reported to PJM shall be excluded from any energy, capacity or transmission loads submitted by FirstEnergy to PJM for load obligations of AEC. 11. This Agreement shall be in full force and effect and binding on the Parties upon the first day of energy delivery by Calpine to the Customer and shall remain in effect until Calpine’s responsibilities and obligations as LSE of the Customer terminate. Calpine shall provide not less than thirty (30) days written notice of termination of this Agreement to FirstEnergy. Unless otherwise agreed to by the Parties, termination of Calpine as the LSE of the Customer shall occur at the next regularly scheduled meter reading date of the Customer after notification of termination. Termination of this Agreement shall not relieve the Parties of any obligations accrued or accruing prior to such termination. 12. FirstEnergy’s liability pursuant to the services rendered under this Agreement, whether based upon contract, tort, breach of warranty, professional negligence (including errors, omissions, or other professional acts) or otherwise, including claims against employees, agents, and officers shall be limited to the total amount of compensation paid to FirstEnergy under this Agreement. 13. No Party shall be liable to the other Party or its affiliates, for claims for incidental, special, indirect or consequential damages of any nature connected with or arising out of the performance or nonperformance of this Agreement.

2022 CONSOLIDATED AGREEMENT
WHEREAS, on February 24, 2011, the Pennsylvania Public Utility Commission
("Commission" or “PaPUC”) approved the merger of FirstEnergy Corp. ("FirstEnergy") and Allegheny
Energy, Inc. ("AE"), under which AE would become a subsidiary of FirstEnergy ("FE-AE Merger");
and
WHEREAS, FirstEnergy is the parent company of Metropolitan Edison Company ("Met-Ed"),
Pennsylvania Electric Company ("Penelec") and West Penn Power Company ("West Penn"); and
WHEREAS, Mid-Atlantic Interstate Transmission, LLC (“MAIT”) is a subsidiary of FirstEnergy
that owns and operates certain electric facilities used for the transmission of wholesale electric energy
(MAIT, Met-Ed, Penelec, and West Penn collectively, with FirstEnergy, “FE”); and
WHEREAS, Met-Ed, Penelec, West Penn, and MAIT deliver, either directly or indirectly,
electricity to member cooperatives of the Pennsylvania Rural Electric Association ("PREA'') and
Allegheny Electric Cooperative, Inc. ("AEC") (PREA/AEC collectively, with FE, the "Parties"); and
WHEREAS, PREA/AEC and its member cooperatives are dependent upon the combined FE
system for electric delivery service to at least 225 PREA/AEC delivery points; and
WHEREAS, PREA/AEC desires to ensure reliable delivery service to its delivery points for the
foreseeable future; and
WHEREAS, FE desires to provide and enhance reliable delivery service to the PREA/AEC
delivery points; and
WHEREAS, PREA/AEC and FE recognize that FE has historically made significant investment
in its transmission and distribution infrastructure, including for projects and maintenance devoted to
circuits that both serve FE customers and have an impact on service to PREA/AEC, and that the amounts
set forth below are consistent with recent levels of expenditures; and
WHEREAS, FE and PREA/AEC worked cooperatively to consolidate into one document the
operative terms, conditions, and commitments contained within the following agreements between the
Parties following consummation of the FE-AE Merger ("2014 Consolidated Agreement"): a) the Joint
Petition For Full Settlement of the Restructuring Plans of Metropolitan Edison and Pennsylvania Electric
Company and Related Dockets and Related Court Proceedings at Commission Docket Nos. R-00974008
and R-00974009 dated September 23, 1998 ("Restructuring Agreement"); b) the Joint Petition for
Settlement of Proceeding in Investigation of Metropolitan Edison Company, Pennsylvania Electric
Company and Pennsylvania Power Company Reliability Performance at Commission Docket No. 1-
00040102 dated September 29, 2004; c) the Joint Petition for Settlement by Metropolitan Edison
Company, Pennsylvania Electric Company and Pennsylvania Power Company's Petition to Amend
Recomputed Benchmarks for Electric Distribution Reliability at Commission Docket No. P-00042115
dated December 8, 2005; d) the PREA/AEC Settlement Agreement dated November 4, 2005 clarifying
prior agreements between the Parties related to Commission Docket Nos. R-00974008 and I-00040102;
e) the PREA/AEC Settlement Agreement dated February 21, 2006; f) the PREA/AEC Settlement
2
Agreement dated August 25, 2006 related to Commission Docket No. R-00061366; g) the letter dated
January 29, 2008 from Vince Kaminski to Scott Johnson regarding the Reliability Standard Adjustment
for the Hollenback delivery point; h) the Agreement dated October 25, 2010 and subsequent Joint Petition
for Partial Settlement related to the FE-AE Merger; and i) the GPU Energy, Allegheny Electric
Cooperative, Inc., Pennsylvania Rural Electric Association - Agreement on Joint Principles on Reliability
and Reliability Standards for Cooperative Delivery Points Served via the GPU Energy Delivery System
dated March 8, 1999; and
WHEREAS, on November 24, 2014, the Parties entered into a Settlement Agreement (“2014
Extension Agreement”), in connection with FE’s August 2014 rate filings at Commission Docket Nos. R2014-2428745 (Met-Ed), R-2014-2428743 (Penelec), and R-2014-2428742 (West Penn), to extend and
modify the Joint Petition Process (“JPP”) initially started under the PaPUC Dockets Nos. R-00974008 and
R-00974009, as amended by subsequent proceedings, for five years so that the JPP would be in place
through 2022; and
WHEREAS, AEC is party to separate Amended and Restated Wheeling and Supplemental Power
Agreements (“WASP Agreements”) dated as of August 5, 2021 with Penelec, Met-Ed, and Jersey Central
Power and Light Company (“JCP&L”), which are designated respectively as Service Agreement Nos.
4222, 4223, and 4221 under the PJM Tariff and filed with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission
(“FERC”); and
WHEREAS, the WASP Agreements, among other things, govern interconnection and coordinated
operation of the Parties’ systems and Allegheny’s use of certain distribution facilities to enable Allegheny
to serve its wholesale loads; and
WHEREAS, FE has provided to AEC notice of termination of the WASP Agreements as of
October 1, 2022; and
WHEREAS, the Parties have agreed to again extend the JPP initially started under Commission
Docket Nos. R-00974008 and R-00974009, as amended by subsequent proceedings, for ten years so that
the JPP will be in place through planning year 2032 (for the 2033 construction year) as a part of a
comprehensive resolution of issues that could be raised in connection with the termination of the WASP
Agreements; and
WHEREAS, as part of the 2014 Consolidated Agreement, 2014 Extension Agreement, and
subsequent discussions in 2022 to again extend the JPP, FE and PREA/AEC agreed to work cooperatively
to consolidate into this document (“2022 Consolidated Agreement”) the operative terms, conditions and
commitments contained within the 2014 Consolidated Agreement, 2014 Extension Agreement, and the
results of their 2022 negotiations; and
NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual covenants and promises herein, FirstEnergy,
on its own behalf and on behalf of Met-Ed, Penelec, West Penn, and MAIT, and PREA/AEC, on behalf
of itself and of its member cooperatives, hereby enter into this 2022 Consolidated Agreement to restate
the obligations and rights of the Parties and agree as follows:
3
A. General Terms
1. The Parties acknowledge and agree that FE shall adhere to the retail distribution reliability
standards established by the Commission's reliability rulemaking at Docket No. L-00970120 dated April
23, 1998, 52 Pa. Code § 57.191-57.198, as well as any other future Commission reliability directives
affecting FE’s retail customers. Adherence to those standards and the terms of this 2022 Consolidated
Agreement, including the IDI and IFI Standards defined in Paragraph 9 below, is expected to allow FE to
operate and maintain its transmission and distribution systems as part of its continuing commitment to
improve system reliability for all retail and wholesale customers.
2. This settlement agreement shall not be construed to modify the terms of the JPP, as
amended and restated, or any other terms and conditions of the 2014 Consolidated Agreement and 2014
Extension Agreement, as modified, unless specifically provided in this settlement agreement. The
Parties agree that the terms of the JPP, the 2014 Consolidated Agreement, the 2014 Extension
Agreement, and all other terms and conditions of agreements between the Parties, have been fully
captured and are accurately contained within this currently effective 2022 Consolidated Agreement,
effective upon the date that FERC accepts this 2022 Consolidated Agreement for filing.
3. The Parties agree that compliance with the provisions of this 2022 Consolidated
Agreement is subject to the existing enforcement rights in the JPP, as most recently restated in the 2014
Consolidated Agreement and 2014 Extension Agreement and as restated herein.
4. For the period of the effective date of this 2022 Consolidated Agreement through
December 31, 2032, PREA/AEC agrees that it shall not intervene in any proceeding filed by FE or its
subsidiaries before the PaPUC, including but not limited to proceedings pertaining to rate changes, long
term infrastructure improvement plans, distribution system improvement charges, change of control or
ownership, and certificates of public convenience (unless such certificate of public convenience or change
of control filings involve the full or partial acquisition of one or more member cooperatives or a
cooperative's service territory), except that PREA/AEC may intervene in any such proceeding or filings
in which FE or its subsidiaries otherwise propose changes in their operational terms and conditions of
service under which one or more PREA/AEC member cooperatives are receiving service or are otherwise
directly impacted. PREA/AEC retains its right to intervene in any PaPUC-initiated investigations or to
initiate a complaint on PREA/AEC's own behalf or to intervene in any proceedings initiated by parties
other than FE.
5. Extending the JPP process as defined herein means extending all parts of the JPP currently
in effect on the date hereof, as it may be subsequently amended by the mutual agreement of the Parties,
through the end of the JPP process as agreed upon herein.
6. FE also confirms that the former AE's consent is not required and that FE shall be bound,
to the extent necessary to achieve the goals of this 2022 Consolidated Agreement, to include and perform
the requirements of the JPP on FE's West Penn system.
7. All of the foregoing recitals, including the various agreements referenced therein, are
incorporated into, and are an integral part of, the terms of this 2022 Consolidated Agreement to the extent
4
they remain in effect. Notwithstanding anything herein to the contrary, this 2022 Consolidated Agreement
is not intended to supersede or nullify any of the prior orders or agreements which contain the provisions
noted herein. This 2022 Consolidated Agreement synthesizes those prior orders and agreements for clarity
and ease of reference and shall be the reference point for all questions related to the JPP. In case of a
conflict between a provision of this 2022 Consolidated Agreement and a provision of a prior order or
agreement, which provision has not been superseded by time or a subsequent agreement, the provision(s)
of the prior order or agreement shall control.
8. This 2022 Consolidated Agreement intentionally does not contain provisions which are
expired or otherwise no longer applicable to the relationship between the parties.
B. PREA/AEC – FE Reliability Standards
9. The following Interruption Duration Index (“IDI”) and Interruption Frequency Index
(“IFI”) Standards (collectively, “Standards”) apply for purposes of this 2022 Consolidated Agreement, as
approved by the Commission1
